[[File:Hozukyō (Kameoka).JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Entrance to {{ill|lt=Hozu Gorge|Q10887680|WD=Q10887680|1=Hozu Gorge}}}}{{small|Uketa Shrine stands on the left bank; beyond the {{ill|lt=Sagano Line|Q1073011|WD=Q1073011|1=Sagano Line}} on the right bank is {{ill|lt=Kuwata Shrine#Kuwata Shrine (Kameoka Shinomachi Yamamoto)|Q11537594|WD=Q11537594|lt=Kuwata Shrine|1=Kuwada Shrine}}.}}]]
'''Uketa Shrine''' (うけたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Hozu-chō Tateiwa, {{ill|lt=Kameoka|Q633996|WD=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|WD=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} {{ill|lt=candidate shrine|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}.

It stands in eastern {{ill|lt=Kameoka|Q633996|WD=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}, at the entrance to {{ill|lt=Hozu Gorge|Q10887680|WD=Q10887680|1=Hozu Gorge}}, where the river's name changes from "{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōi River|1=UNKNOWN}}" to "{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hozu River|1=UNKNOWN}}." Across the river stands {{ill|lt=Kuwata Shrine#Kuwata Shrine (Kameoka Shinomachi Yamamoto)|Q11537594|WD=Q11537594|lt=Kuwata Shrine|1=Kuwada Shrine}}. Together with Kuwata Shrine, it is connected with traditions about the excavation of Hozu Gorge.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|WD=Q10935105|lt=Ōyamakui-no-Kami|Q10935105|WD=Q10935105|1=Oyamakui no Kami}} (おおやまくいのかみ)
* {{ill|lt=Ichikishimahime|Q11059454|WD=Q11059454|WD=Q11059454|lt=Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|1=Ichikishima-hime}} (いちきしまひめのみこと) - also called Sayorihime-no-Mikoto.

=== History ===
Because shrine buildings and documents were destroyed by military fire in the {{ill|lt=Eiroku|Q1143341|WD=Q1143341|1=Eiroku}} era ({{ill|lt=1558|Q6601|WD=Q6601|1=1558}}-{{ill|lt=1570|Q6659|WD=Q6659|1=1570}}), detailed origins are unclear<ref name=setsumei>Explanatory board in the precincts.</ref>. The enshrined deity Ōyamakui-no-Kami is said to be a deity who came from Izumo to develop the Tanba region, then a lake area, and to have begun excavating Hozu Gorge from the site of {{ill|lt=Kuwata Shrine|Q11537594|WD=Q11537594|1=Kuwada Shrine}} opposite Uketa Shrine<ref name=setsumei/>. It is said the shrine name "Uketa" comes from accepting (uketa) this groundbreaking hoe-rite for that development<ref name=setsumei/>. Traditions that the Kameoka Basin was once a lake remain in many nearby places (see "{{ill|lt=Kameoka Basin#Lake tradition|Q11181997|WD=Q11181997|1=Kameoka Basin}}" for details).

Shrine tradition gives its foundation as {{ill|lt=Wadō|Q1373026|WD=Q1373026|1=Wadō (era)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=709|Q23514|WD=Q23514|1=709}}). Because the shrine site was called "Iwao," it is identified as a {{ill|lt=candidate shrine|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} for the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} listed in the mid-{{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} as "Ishio Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Kuwata District|Q11537600|WD=Q11537600|1=Kuwada district}}, {{ill|lt=Tanba Province|Q954511|WD=Q954511|1=Tanba Province}}. For unclear reasons, there is also a theory identifying it as Matsuo Shrine, another shikinaisha of Kuwata District<ref>Other candidate shrines for Matsuo Shrine include {{ill|lt=Matsuo Shrine (Kameoka)|Q11529679|WD=Q11529679|lt=Matsuo Shrine|1=Matsuo Shrine (Kameoka)}} in Asahi-chō, Kameoka.</ref>.

After the destruction by fire in the Eiroku era, it was moved to Miyanoue (present Hozu Hachimangū)<ref name=chimei>''Place Names of Kyoto Prefecture'', entry for Hozu village.</ref>. It returned to the current site in the {{ill|lt=Kan'ei|Q1192913|WD=Q1192913|1=Kan'ei}} era ({{ill|lt=1624|Q6821|WD=Q6821|1=1624}}-{{ill|lt=1645|Q6925|WD=Q6925|1=1645}})<ref name=chimei/>, but at Miyanoue a divided spirit is still enshrined as a {{ill|lt=tongū|Q11664877|WD=Q11664877|1=tongū}}.

In the early modern period, Hozu Gorge was called "Uketa Gorge," and with Uketa Shrine, the Kuwata Shrine on the opposite bank was also called "Uketa Shrine" or "Uketa Shrine (floating-field shrine)."

=== Precincts ===
<gallery>
File:Uketa-jinja (Kameoka) honden.JPG|Honden
File:Uketa-jinja (Kameoka) torii.JPG|Torii
</gallery>

=== Subsidiary shrines ===
'''Precinct sub-shrine'''
* Inari Shrine - located beside the honden.

'''Off-site shrine'''
[[File:Hozu-hachimangū keidai.JPG|thumb|200px|right|{{center|Hozu Hachimangū precincts}}{{small|Hachimangū at back left; Uketa Shrine {{ill|lt=tongū|Q11664877|WD=Q11664877|1=tongū}} at right. Both are Kyoto Prefecture designated cultural properties.}}]]
* {{ill|lt=Tongū|Q11664877|WD=Q11664877|1=Tongū}}
*: Located in the precincts of Hozu Hachimangū (21 Miyanoue, Hozu-chō, Kameoka). Uketa Shrine is said to have been temporarily moved here from the Eiroku era to the Kan'ei era, and after returning, a divided spirit continued to be enshrined here as a tongū ({{ill|lt=otabisho|Q11489117|WD=Q11489117|1=Otabisho}}). Its style is one-bay {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}}. Hachimangū is said to have drifted here from Hosokawa village in Kita-Kuwata District during the Kan'ei era and was rebuilt on the former Uketa Shrine site after Uketa's return<ref name=chimei/>. On the hill to the north remains a bell tower as a relic of Wakōin, the former shrine-temple (now abolished){{ill|lt=jingūji|Q1074971|WD=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}}. These three structures, Hozu Hachimangū's honden and bell tower and Uketa Shrine's tongū, are designated cultural properties of Kyoto Prefecture<ref name="教育委員会">[http://www.kyoto-be.ne.jp/bunkazai/cms/?page_id=200 Kyoto Prefecture designated/registered cultural properties] (Kyoto Prefectural Board of Education).</ref><ref>[https://www.city.kameoka.kyoto.jp/shakai/bunkazai/hozuhachiman-uketa.html New Kyoto Prefecture cultural-property designation for Kameoka cultural assets] (Kameoka City website).</ref>.

=== Festivals ===
* Autumn Grand Festival ({{ill|lt=October 21|Q2960|WD=Q2960|1=October 21}})
*: Also called the "Hozu Fire Festival." It begins with the eve festival; the divine spirit is welcomed from the main sanctuary to the tongū within Hozu Hachimangū.

